  "text": "This can be relaxed to allow a probability δ of failure. Theorem 16 states that the relaxations notions of differential privacy used in some previous work still imply privacy in the face of arbitrary side information. This is not the case for all possible relaxations, even very natural ones. For example, if one replaced the multiplicative notion of distance used in differential privacy with total variation distance, then the following \"sanitizer\" would be deemed private: choose an index i ∈ {1, . . . , n} uniformly at random and publish the entire record of individual i together with his or her identity (example 2 in [CITATION_1] ). Such a \"sanitizer\" would not be meaningful at all, regardless of side information.",
